h3. Issue Summary
When a global template has been changed, we are not able to edit the template at the space-level

h3. Steps to Reproduce
# Navigate to *Settings > Global Templates and Blueprints*;
# Scroll down to the *Meeting Notes* template and edit it (not the index one);
# Add any changes to it and save it;
# Navigate to any space you are a space admin and access *Space Settings > Content Tools > Templates*;
# Scroll down to the *Meeting Notes* template and edit it (not the index one);
# Add any changes to it and hit the *Save* button.

h3. Expected Results
The changes are saved as usual.

h3. Actual Results
An error is thrown in the screen saying "_Unable to communicate with server. Saving is not possible at the moment._"

*Notes*
* After hitting the save button, a 500 error occurs in the saving endpoint {{https://dorime.atlassian.net/wiki/rest/api/template}} with the below response:
{code:json}
{
    "statusCode": 500,
    "message": "javax.persistence.PersistenceException: org.hibernate.HibernateException: Found shared references to a collection: com.atlassian.confluence.pages.templates.PageTemplate.templateAttachments"
}
{code}
* (!) This is also reproducible with some other templates;
* (i) If you have edited your space template prior to the global template changes, you will be able to keep editing it, as long as you do not reset it to default.

h3. Workaround
For now, you can:
* Edit the space template, copy its content, and create a new custom template to add your changes there adn use it while we work to fix this issue;
* Reset the global template.

Page restriction editing permissions for page creators are mentioned in the documentation [Assign space permissions|https://support.atlassian.com/confluence-cloud/docs/assign-space-permissions/] as follows:
{quote}
They can edit the page restrictions on any page they themselves create, even if the space level Add/Delete permission under Restrictions is revoked.
{quote}
However in reality, the page creators will not do that without Add/Delete permission under Restrictions. The quoted text should be removed from the document.

h3. Issue Summary
The [Public Links|https://confluence.atlassian.com/ge/public-links-979425312.html] feature came as an alternative for the good and old Anonymous Access we have in Confluence, opening our usability of Confluence more dynamic.
Though, it seems that when we are enabling/disabling this feature on our pages, it is not getting logged correctly in the Audit Log, letting the order of the actions in the wrong sequence, date, and time.

h3. Steps to Reproduce
# Navigate to the Confluence settings and make sure that the *[Public links|https://confluence.atlassian.com/ge/public-links-979425312.html]* feature is enabled;
# Navigate to a page;
# In the top-right corner, click over the *Share* button;
# Mark the toggle button to make the page publicly shared;
# After the toggle gets green, disable it;
# Navigate to the Confluence Audit Logs and observe the latest log at the top of the list.

h3. Expected Results
The first even, from top to bottom, is the _Public Links page settings disabled_ one, and the second one is the _Public Links page settings enabled_.

h3. Actual Results
The logs are not there.

*Notes*
* For some times, the event in the audit log is not even registered;
* The logs get registered to a day before - you can find then by searching for "_public_", in the audit log;
* The first log that gets registered is the _disabled_ one, and then the _enabled_ one, which doesn't make sense;
* Eventually, after enabling/disabling it on different pages, the logs get registered on the correct day, but in different order and time.

h3. Workaround
Currently there is no known workaround for this behavior. A workaround will be added here when available

h3. Issue Summary
When we try to attach a file that exceeds the attachment maximum size limit in the Confluence site in the Attachments macro, nothing happens but the spinning wheel keeps loading forever.

h3. Steps to Reproduce
# Navigate to *Settings > General Configuration*;
# Edit it and set the attachments maximum size to 100MB, for example;
# Create a new page;
# Insert the *Attachments* macro, then publish the page;
# Drag&drop or search for a file in your computer that is higher than 100BM to try to upload in the page.

h3. Expected Results
A warning message is thrown saying the file exceeds the maximum size set in that Confluence instance.

h3. Actual Results
Nothing happens - the spinning wheel keeps spinning forever.

*Notes*:
* You can use this command (on OSX or Linux) to generate a 300MB file: {{dd if=/dev/zero of=file.txt count=1024 bs=300000}}

h3. Workaround
You can either reduce the size of the file or engage one of your Confluence admins to increase the maximum size limit.

h3. Issue Summary

This issue is happening when profile visibility for a users email address is set to Org Member or Only Me(Admin also). The Org Admin can not view the email address through the Confluence API with either the GET user request or the search user API request. If that Org Admins email address isn't a managed user.

Example API GET User endpoint:
{code:java}
https://<SITE-NAME>.atlassian.net/wiki/rest/api/user?accountId=<Atlassian-Account-ID>{code}
 
h3. Steps to Reproduce
 # Have a user set their profile visibility for emails to *Org Member* or *Anyone(And Admin)*
 # Have a Org Admin who is also a Site Admin run either of the following API calls for the new user with above-mentioned visibility settings configured.
 # You'll notice the HTTP response doesn't provide the email address.

h3. Expected Results

That the email object should be populated:
{code:java}
{
"type": "known",
"accountId": "<ATLASSIAN-ACCOUNT-ID>",
"accountType": "atlassian",
"email": "<EMAIL-ADDRESS-POPULATED>",
"publicName": "<NAME>",
"profilePicture": {
"path": "/wiki/aa-avatar/<ATLASSIAN-ACCOUNT-ID>",
"width": 48,
"height": 48,
"isDefault": false
},
"displayName": "<ACCOUNT-NAME>",
"isExternalCollaborator": false,
"_expandable": {
"operations": "",
"personalSpace": ""
},
"_links": {
"self": "https://<SITE-NAME>.atlassian.net/wiki/rest/api/user?accountId=<ATLASSIAN-ACCOUNT-ID>",
{code}
h3. Actual Results

There is no email address being populated.
{code:java}
{
"type": "known",
"accountId": "<ATLASSIAN-ACCOUNT-ID>",
"accountType": "atlassian",
"email": "",
"publicName": "<NAME>",
"profilePicture": {
"path": "/wiki/aa-avatar/<ATLASSIAN-ACCOUNT-ID>",
"width": 48,
"height": 48,
"isDefault": false
},
"displayName": "<ACCOUNT-NAME>",
"isExternalCollaborator": false,
"_expandable": {
"operations": "",
"personalSpace": ""
},
"_links": {
"self": "https://<SITE-NAME>.atlassian.net/wiki/rest/api/user?accountId=<ATLASSIAN-ACCOUNT-ID>",
"base": "https://<SITE-NAME>.atlassian.net/wiki",
"context": "/wiki"
}
}
{code}
h3. Workaround

*  Users can use the *Org REST API* to generate this information: [Manage an Organization with admin API|https://support.atlassian.com/organization-administration/docs/manage-an-organization-with-the-admin-apis/]
